{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"25be827f-891b-4c8b-8c58-623e6908dc32","content":"## What happened\n\n`DSA.Create()` throws **`PlatformNotSupportedException` on macOS** because Apple's native crypto frameworks (Security.framework / CryptoKit) **do not support DSA**. In earlier .NET versions, an OpenSSL-based fallback handled this on macOS, but that shim has been removed — DSA is now unsupported on Apple platforms.\n\n## How to fix it\n\n**Option 1 — Use BouncyCastle (recommended for legacy verification):**\n\n```csharp\n// dotnet add package BouncyCastle.Cryptography\nusing Org.BouncyCastle.Crypto.Parameters;\nusing Org.BouncyCastle.Security;\n\nvar signer = SignerUtilities.GetSigner(\"SHA256withDSA\");\nsigner.Init(forSigning: false, publicKey);\nsigner.BlockUpdate(data, 0, data.Length);\nbool valid = signer.VerifySignature(signature);\n```\n\nThis is a fully managed implementation — works on **all platforms** with no native dependencies.\n\n**Option 2 — Guard with a runtime check** (if you can tolerate skipping macOS):\n\n```csharp\nif (!OperatingSystem.IsMacOS())\n{\n    using var dsa = DSA.Create();\n    // ...\n}\n```\n\n**Option 3 — Ship OpenSSL on macOS** via Homebrew or a bundled native lib and P/Invoke into it, but this adds deployment complexity.\n\n### Recommendation\n\nGo with **BouncyCastle**. It gives you a single code path across Linux, Windows, and macOS with no native crypto dependency, which is exactly what you need for legacy DSA signature verification.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"905887c1-12f3-4b9a-a567-81edb96422d7","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET compatibility issue related to DSA (Digital Signature Algorithm) and the transition from .NET 10 to .NET 11, specifically on macOS.\n\nLet me think about what I know regarding this topic:\n\nIn .NET, the `DSA.Create()` method on macOS historically used Apple's CommonCrypto/Security framework under the hood. However, Microsoft has been gradually deprecating and removing support for older, less-secure cryptographic algorithms.\n\nStarting with .NET 7+, Microsoft began marking DSA as obsolete on macOS because Apple's platforms don't natively support DSA in their modern security frameworks. The actual removal/breaking change timeline:\n\n\n- Apple's Security framework dropped DSA support, and earlier .NET versions relied on OpenSSL for DSA operations on macOS\n- At some point, `DSA.Create()` started throwing `PlatformNotSupportedException` on macOS instead of working silently\n\nLet me nail down the specifics of when exactly this breaking change occurred and what the precise behavior is between .NET versions. So if the user is experiencing this in April 2026, .NET 11 would indeed be in preview or recently released. The most likely explanation is that DSA support was either removed entirely or an OpenSSL fallback that existed in .NET 10 was discontinued in .NET 11, aligning with the broader industry trend of deprecating legacy cryptographic algorithms. Apple's security frameworks don't support DSA, so any OpenSSL-based workaround that existed in .NET 10 was likely removed in .NET 11. To work around this, I could use BouncyCastle for a managed implementation, conditionally compile to use OpenSSL directly on macOS, or manually handle DSA verification with ASN.1 parsing and a third-party library.","outputTokens":1529},"id":"b2638b91-a550-4374-b3a8-be0952e14f51","timestamp":"2026-04-05T01:02:13.301Z","parentId":"f284ca59-e52a-41f8-bb44-041f30709ca7"}
